Thirty eight randomised controlled comparisons were identified from 22 trials. Most were based on healthy adult participants who were not considered at increased risk of complications. There was no evidence that a shortened fluid fast time increased the risk of complications compared with the standard nil-bymouth regime from midnight. In fact, participants given a drink of water preoperatively were found to have a significantly lower volume of gastric contents than the groups who followed a standard fasting regime.

